<div class="hero">
  <div class="breadcrumb" style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--ink3);margin-bottom:16px;"><a href="index.html" style="color:var(--ink3);text-decoration:none;">Home</a> › BMI Chart for Men Over 60</div>
  <h1>BMI Chart for<br><em>Men Over 60</em></h1>
  <p>Healthy BMI ranges, average BMI by age, and what the numbers actually mean for men in their 60s and beyond.</p>
</div>

<div style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--ink3);margin:0 auto 24px;max-width:720px;padding:0 20px 16px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">Reviewed by <strong>Sarah Mitchell, BSc Nutrition</strong> · Last updated: <strong>June 2025</strong></div>

<div class="container">


  <div class="answer-box">
    <div class="answer-label">Healthy BMI range for men over 60</div>
    <div class="answer-value">18.5 – 24.9</div>
    <div class="answer-sub">Standard WHO range · some research suggests up to 27 may be acceptable after 65</div>
  </div>

  <div class="info-grid">
    <div class="info-box">
      <div class="lbl">Average BMI for men aged 60–69</div>
      <div class="val">~28.0</div>
    </div>
    <div class="info-box">
      <div class="lbl">Asian BMI healthy ceiling</div>
      <div class="val">≤ 22.9</div>
    </div>
    <div class="info-box">
      <div class="lbl">Overweight starts at</div>
      <div class="val">25.0 (or 23.0 Asian)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="info-box">
      <div class="lbl">Obese starts at</div>
      <div class="val">30.0 (or 27.5 Asian)</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">

    <h2>BMI Chart for Men Over 60 by Height and Weight</h2>
    <p>The table below shows the healthy weight range (BMI 18.5–24.9) for men of different heights. Use this to quickly find your target weight range.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Height</th>
          <th>Healthy Weight Range (BMI 18.5–24.9)</th>
          <th>Overweight starts at (BMI 25)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>5'5" / 165 cm</td><td>50–68 kg / 111–149 lb</td><td>68 kg / 150 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5'7" / 170 cm</td><td>53–72 kg / 118–158 lb</td><td>72 kg / 159 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5'9" / 175 cm</td><td>57–76 kg / 125–168 lb</td><td>77 kg / 169 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5'11" / 180 cm</td><td>60–81 kg / 132–178 lb</td><td>81 kg / 179 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>6'1" / 185 cm</td><td>63–85 kg / 140–188 lb</td><td>86 kg / 189 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>6'3" / 190 cm</td><td>67–90 kg / 147–198 lb</td><td>90 kg / 199 lb</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>For your exact BMI use our <a href="bmi-calculator.html">free BMI Calculator</a> — enter your height and weight and get an instant result.</p>

    <h2>Average BMI for Men Over 60</h2>
    <p>The average BMI for men aged 60 to 69 is approximately 28.0, which sits in the overweight category. This reflects a broad population trend — most men in their 60s carry more weight than is considered optimal for long-term health.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Age group (men)</th><th>Average BMI</th><th>Category</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>60–64</td><td>~28.2</td><td>Overweight</td></tr>
        <tr><td>65–69</td><td>~27.8</td><td>Overweight</td></tr>
        <tr><td>70–74</td><td>~27.3</td><td>Overweight</td></tr>
        <tr><td>75+</td><td>~26.1</td><td>Overweight / upper normal</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout"><p>💡 Average BMI tends to decrease slightly after age 70, partly because of natural muscle and weight loss with age (sarcopenia), not necessarily improved health. A lower BMI in older men is not always a positive sign if it reflects muscle loss.</p></div>

    <h2>Does Healthy BMI Change After 60?</h2>
    <p>The official WHO healthy BMI range of 18.5 to 24.9 does not change with age. However, research on older adults has found a more complex picture. Some studies suggest that men over 65 with a BMI of 25 to 27 may have slightly lower mortality risk than those at the very low end of normal weight. This is sometimes called the "obesity paradox."</p>
    <p>The most important factor is body composition — specifically, maintaining muscle mass while keeping body fat, especially visceral fat, in check. Two men can have identical BMIs with very different health profiles depending on how much of their weight is muscle versus fat.</p>

    <h2>BMI for Asian Men Over 60</h2>
    <p>For men of Asian descent, standard BMI cutoffs underestimate health risk. Research consistently shows that Asian men develop cardiovascular and metabolic risk at lower BMI levels than Western populations. The recommended Asian-specific cutoffs are:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Category</th><th>Standard BMI</th><th>Asian BMI</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Normal</td><td>18.5 – 24.9</td><td>18.5 – 22.9</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Overweight</td><td>25.0 – 29.9</td><td>23.0 – 27.4</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Obese</td><td>30.0+</td><td>27.5+</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>If you are of Asian descent, use our <a href="asian-bmi-calculator.html">Asian BMI Calculator</a> to see where you stand against these thresholds.</p>

    <h2>Key Health Risks for Men Over 60 at High BMI</h2>
    <p>Carrying excess weight after 60 increases risk of several serious conditions. The most significant for men in this age group are cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, sleep apnoea, osteoarthritis in weight-bearing joints, and certain cancers including colorectal cancer.</p>
    <p>Waist circumference is an important additional measure. For men, a waist above 94 cm (37 inches) indicates elevated risk, and above 102 cm (40 inches) indicates high risk — regardless of BMI.</p>

    <h2>Maintaining a Healthy Weight After 60</h2>
    <p>Weight management after 60 is harder for several reasons. Metabolism slows, muscle mass decreases (making it easier to gain fat at the same calorie intake), and hormonal changes affect fat distribution. The most effective strategies for men over 60 are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Resistance training at least twice a week to preserve muscle mass — this is more important after 60 than at any earlier age</li>
      <li>Adequate protein intake, around 1.6 to 2.0 g per kg of body weight per day, to support muscle retention</li>
      <li>A moderate calorie deficit if weight loss is the goal — use our <a href="calorie-deficit-calculator.html">Calorie Deficit Calculator</a> to find your target</li>
      <li>Cardio exercise for cardiovascular health — 150 minutes of moderate activity per week is the standard guideline</li>
      <li>Regular monitoring of waist circumference, not just BMI</li>
    </ul>


    <h2>BMI, Muscle Loss, and Metabolic Syndrome After 60</h2>
    <p>One of the most important things to understand about BMI after 60 is that the same BMI can represent very different health states depending on body composition. Two men at BMI 26 — one with 20% body fat and strong muscle mass, one with 30% body fat and significant sarcopenia — have very different metabolic risk profiles.</p>
    <p>After 60, men lose muscle mass at approximately <strong>1–2% per year</strong> if not actively training. This means that even if the scale stays the same, the ratio of fat to muscle shifts unfavourably — a phenomenon sometimes called "sarcopenic obesity." The man at BMI 24 who hasn't exercised in 10 years may carry more visceral fat than his BMI suggests.</p>
    <p>Three metrics are more informative than BMI alone for men over 60:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Waist circumference:</strong> Above 102 cm (40 inches) is high risk; 94–102 cm is elevated risk — use this alongside BMI</li>
      <li><strong>Grip strength:</strong> A proxy for overall muscle mass and functional fitness — low grip strength is independently associated with all-cause mortality in older men</li>
      <li><strong>Waist-to-height ratio:</strong> Below 0.5 is low risk; above 0.6 is high risk — use our <a href="waist-to-height-ratio.html">Waist-to-Height Ratio Calculator</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>FAQ: BMI for Men Over 60</h2>
    <div class="faq-section" style="margin-top:0;">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is BMI 27 healthy for a man over 60?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">BMI 27 puts a man in the "overweight" category by standard WHO guidelines. However, some research suggests that for adults over 65, a BMI in the 25–27 range may be associated with better outcomes than the standard healthy range of 18.5–24.9. This is thought to be due to nutritional reserves during illness. That said, waist circumference and muscle mass are better indicators of health risk than BMI at this age. If waist circumference is under 94 cm and physical fitness is maintained, a BMI of 27 is unlikely to represent a significant health concern for most men over 60.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the most important thing for health after 60 — weight loss or muscle gain?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">For most men over 60, preserving and building muscle mass (through resistance training and adequate protein) delivers more health benefit than weight loss alone. Muscle mass supports metabolic rate, bone density, functional independence, and cardiovascular health. A man who loses 5 kg of fat while maintaining muscle is in a far better health position than one who loses 5 kg of mixed fat and muscle. If weight loss is needed, prioritise preserving muscle by using a moderate deficit (300–500 kcal/day) with 1.6–2.0 g protein/kg/day and resistance training.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does BMI account for age?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">No — standard BMI categories (underweight, healthy, overweight, obese) are the same for all adults regardless of age. This is a recognised limitation: the same BMI in a 65-year-old represents a different body composition than in a 25-year-old due to age-related muscle loss and fat redistribution. Some researchers argue for age-adjusted BMI thresholds, but official guidelines (WHO, CDC, NHS) have not adopted this approach. In practice, clinicians often supplement BMI with waist circumference and other markers when assessing older adults.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-callout"><p>⚠️ BMI is a screening tool, not a diagnosis. Men over 60 with concerns about weight, cardiovascular risk, or metabolic health should discuss their individual situation with a doctor.</p></div>

